<h1>Borrowed Chords</h1>
<p>
  Borrowed chords are chords taken from the parallel minor (or another mode)
  and used temporarily in a major-key context. The most common example is the
  <strong>bVII</strong> chord — in C major, that is B♭ major.
</p>
<p>
  The second row of this chart borrows B♭ from C Mixolydian. The normaliser
  leaves it alone because <code>Bb</code> is already spelled correctly.
</p>
<p>
  The third row introduces <code>A7</code> as a secondary dominant — V7/ii,
  pointing toward the Dm chord that follows. Secondary dominants temporarily
  tonicise a chord other than the home tonic.
</p>
